WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.122
Chapter Six. The Argument. The first real snow came at

00:00:03.122 --> 00:00:06.243
noon and was still falling at three, and Desh was

00:00:06.243 --> 00:00:09.365
kneading dough with his sleeves pushed up to the elbow.

00:00:09.365 --> 00:00:12.486
The kitchen window framed the snow the way a screen

00:00:12.486 --> 00:00:15.608
frames a video — the small, deliberate rectangle of a

00:00:15.608 --> 00:00:18.729
world rendered for attention. Flakes drifted past the glass at

00:00:18.729 --> 00:00:21.851
varying speeds, some hesitating in updrafts, some committing themselves to

00:00:21.851 --> 00:00:24.972
the ground in straight, indifferent lines. The garden beds Lena

00:00:24.972 --> 00:00:28.094
had been turning since November were losing their definition. The

00:00:28.094 --> 00:00:31.215
greenhouse roof was whitening at the edges. By morning the

00:00:31.215 --> 00:00:34.337
path to the cottages would be a guess. He turned

00:00:34.337 --> 00:00:37.458
the dough a quarter rotation and folded it over itself.

00:00:37.458 --> 00:00:40.580
The motion was automatic. He had been making bread once

00:00:40.580 --> 00:00:43.701
a week since he arrived, on Wednesdays, because Wednesdays were

00:00:43.701 --> 00:00:46.823
when the gathering met and a fresh loaf gave him

00:00:46.823 --> 00:00:49.944
something to bring that wasn't an opinion. He had not

00:00:49.944 --> 00:00:53.066
been sleeping well. Last night had been the worst of

00:00:53.066 --> 00:00:56.187
the recent run — the kind of insomnia that did

00:00:56.187 --> 00:00:59.309
not feel anxious so much as administrative, his mind moving

00:00:59.309 --> 00:01:02.430
through inventories he had not asked it to assemble. The

00:01:02.430 --> 00:01:05.552
pantry. The oil rotation. The state of the stockpot June

00:01:05.552 --> 00:01:08.674
had said needed re-tinning. The conversations he had not yet

00:01:08.674 --> 00:01:11.795
had with his mother. The emails from his old startup

00:01:11.795 --> 00:01:14.917
that had stopped coming three weeks ago, which he had

00:01:14.917 --> 00:01:18.038
not noticed at the time and which now, in the

00:01:18.038 --> 00:01:21.160
dark, took up disproportionate space in his thinking. He had

00:01:21.160 --> 00:01:24.281
gotten out of bed at four and come down to

00:01:24.281 --> 00:01:27.403
the kitchen and found the dough he'd started the night

00:01:27.403 --> 00:01:30.524
before perfectly proofed, ready for the oven, and had thought:

00:01:30.524 --> 00:01:33.646
of course it is. Bread does its work whether you

00:01:33.646 --> 00:01:36.767
sleep or not. That is the entire point of bread.

00:01:36.767 --> 00:01:39.889
Now it was past three. The first loaf was on

00:01:39.889 --> 00:01:43.010
a board, cooling under a tea towel. The second —

00:01:43.010 --> 00:01:46.132
the one he was making for the gathering — was

00:01:46.132 --> 00:01:49.253
midway through its first rise. The house was quiet in

00:01:49.253 --> 00:01:52.375
the way it became quiet when snow was falling, the

00:01:52.375 --> 00:01:55.496
silence coming from outside and pressing in through the windows.

00:01:55.496 --> 00:01:58.618
From somewhere upstairs he could hear the faint, uneven clatter

00:01:58.618 --> 00:02:01.739
of Margot's typewriter. She had begun using it last week

00:02:01.739 --> 00:02:04.861
instead of her notebook because she had read somewhere that

00:02:04.861 --> 00:02:07.982
the friction of mechanical writing slowed cognition into something more

00:02:07.982 --> 00:02:11.104
honest. She had told him this earnestly, over coffee. He

00:02:11.104 --> 00:02:14.226
had nodded and not pointed out that this was the

00:02:14.226 --> 00:02:17.347
same logic she had used to justify a ten-day water

00:02:17.347 --> 00:02:20.469
fast in 2023, which she had also told him about.

00:02:20.469 --> 00:02:23.590
He liked Margot. The fact that he could see through

00:02:23.590 --> 00:02:26.712
her did not change this. He could see through everyone.

00:02:26.712 --> 00:02:29.833
It was the curse and the comfort of growing up

00:02:29.833 --> 00:02:32.955
in a house full of physicians: he had learned to

00:02:32.955 --> 00:02:36.076
read people the way other children learned to read picture

00:02:36.076 --> 00:02:39.198
books. His parents diagnosed across a dinner table — a

00:02:39.198 --> 00:02:42.319
tilt of the head, an unconscious cough, the particular way

00:02:42.319 --> 00:02:45.441
someone stirred their tea. Differential diagnosis as a parlor trick.

00:02:45.441 --> 00:02:48.562
Desh had absorbed it without permission, the way a child

00:02:48.562 --> 00:02:51.684
absorbs language, and now he could not turn it off.

00:02:51.684 --> 00:02:54.805
He punched the dough down. The yeast released its sweet,

00:02:54.805 --> 00:02:57.927
slightly alcoholic breath into the air. He covered the bowl

00:02:57.927 --> 00:03:01.048
with a clean towel and washed his hands and looked

00:03:01.048 --> 00:03:04.170
out the window again, and the snow was still coming,

00:03:04.170 --> 00:03:07.291
and the world was getting smaller in the comforting way

00:03:07.291 --> 00:03:10.413
the world gets smaller when the weather decides it for

00:03:10.413 --> 00:03:13.534
you. The notebook was on the counter beside the spice

00:03:13.534 --> 00:03:16.656
rack, open to a fresh page. He had started keeping

00:03:16.656 --> 00:03:19.778
it on the second day at the Keeping House, out

00:03:19.778 --> 00:03:22.899
of habit and out of an instinct he did not

00:03:22.899 --> 00:03:26.021
entirely trust — that anything not recorded would dissolve. The

00:03:26.021 --> 00:03:29.142
first entries were straightforward: dates, dishes, who cooked, what came

00:03:29.142 --> 00:03:32.264
out of the pantry. Day Two. Ribollita, Lena lead. Used

00:03:32.264 --> 00:03:35.385
the last of the cannellini. Margot ate two bowls but

00:03:35.385 --> 00:03:38.507
talked through the second one, which is a tell. The

00:03:38.507 --> 00:03:41.628
entries had grown. By the second week they included weather

00:03:41.628 --> 00:03:44.750
and small dialogue, and by the third week Desh had

00:03:44.750 --> 00:03:47.871
stopped pretending it was a recipe archive. It was something

00:03:47.871 --> 00:03:50.993
else. He did not yet know what to call it,

00:03:50.993 --> 00:03:54.114
and the not-knowing was the only thing that kept him

00:03:54.114 --> 00:03:57.236
from deleting it, because the moment he could name it

00:03:57.236 --> 00:04:00.357
he would feel the urge to make it efficient, and

00:04:00.357 --> 00:04:03.479
the moment he made it efficient it would die. He

00:04:03.479 --> 00:04:06.600
looked at the page. Today, so far, he had written

00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:09.722
three lines. Snow, finally. Loaves times two. Fen has been

00:04:09.722 --> 00:04:12.843
re-reading the same Weil book for four days. The kettle

00:04:12.843 --> 00:04:15.965
is making the noise again. He picked up the pen

00:04:15.965 --> 00:04:19.086
and added a fourth. Gathering tonight. I am bringing bread

00:04:19.086 --> 00:04:22.208
because I do not know what else I have to

00:04:22.208 --> 00:04:25.330
say. He read the line back. He did not like

00:04:25.330 --> 00:04:28.451
it. He drew a single thin line through it. He

00:04:28.451 --> 00:04:31.573
did not erase it. The kitchen door opened and Lena

00:04:31.573 --> 00:04:34.694
came in from the cold, stamping snow from her boots

00:04:34.694 --> 00:04:37.816
on the mat, the shoulders of her wool coat gone

00:04:37.816 --> 00:04:40.937
white in the short walk from the greenhouse. "It's coming

00:04:40.937 --> 00:04:44.059
down hard," she said. "I see it." "Six inches by

00:04:44.059 --> 00:04:47.180
morning, June thinks." She unwound her scarf and hung it

00:04:47.180 --> 00:04:50.302
by the door, registering, as she always did, the temperature

00:04:50.302 --> 00:04:53.423
of the room, the state of the counters, the loaves,

00:04:53.423 --> 00:04:56.545
the bowl under the towel, the open notebook, in the

00:04:56.545 --> 00:04:59.666
time it took most people to register the existence of

00:04:59.666 --> 00:05:02.788
a kitchen. "You've been up since when?" He smiled. "Don't."

00:05:02.788 --> 00:05:05.909
"I'm not." "You are." "I'm asking." "Four. And I'm fine.

00:05:05.909 --> 00:05:09.031
The bread is fine. Don't take my pulse." She laughed

00:05:09.031 --> 00:05:12.152
— the small, slightly rueful laugh she had developed in

00:05:12.152 --> 00:05:15.274
the weeks since the morning of the pipe, the morning

00:05:15.274 --> 00:05:18.395
Noor had said you've rearranged the coriander three times. The

00:05:18.395 --> 00:05:21.517
laugh was the sound of a woman trying not to

00:05:21.517 --> 00:05:24.638
do the thing her body wanted to do. He had

00:05:24.638 --> 00:05:27.760
noticed the change. He had noted it, in his way,

00:05:27.760 --> 00:05:30.882
and not written it down. "I made tea this morning,"

00:05:30.882 --> 00:05:34.003
she said. "There's some left." "I don't want any tea."

00:05:34.003 --> 00:05:37.125
"I know you don't." She was already at the counter

00:05:37.125 --> 00:05:40.246
pouring it into a mug. "I'm leaving it here. You

00:05:40.246 --> 00:05:43.368
can drink it or not." He took the mug. He

00:05:43.368 --> 00:05:46.489
drank some of it. It was cold, and the bergamot

00:05:46.489 --> 00:05:49.611
had gone slightly metallic in the pot, and he was

00:05:49.611 --> 00:05:52.732
unaccountably touched. She watched him for a moment with the

00:05:52.732 --> 00:05:55.854
open, unembarrassed attention she had begun to allow herself. Then

00:05:55.854 --> 00:05:58.975
she said, "Are you nervous about tonight?" "Why would I

00:05:58.975 --> 00:06:02.097
be nervous?" "Because Fen has been writing in the library

00:06:02.097 --> 00:06:05.218
for three days and you have been making bread, and

00:06:05.218 --> 00:06:08.340
the last time you two spoke for more than a

00:06:08.340 --> 00:06:11.461
minute it ended with him deciding not to argue with

00:06:11.461 --> 00:06:14.583
you, and people who decide not to argue tend to

00:06:14.583 --> 00:06:17.704
come back having decided to argue, and you've been grinding

00:06:17.704 --> 00:06:20.826
your teeth in your sleep." "You can't possibly know that."

00:06:20.826 --> 00:06:23.947
"You have a small bruise on the inside of your

00:06:23.947 --> 00:06:27.069
lower lip. From where you bite down." He put his

00:06:27.069 --> 00:06:30.190
hand to his mouth. He felt nothing. He took it

00:06:30.190 --> 00:06:33.312
away. "That's not fair," he said. "I'm not being fair.

00:06:33.312 --> 00:06:36.434
I'm being a nurse." She picked up her gloves and

00:06:36.434 --> 00:06:39.555
tucked them under her arm. At the door she paused,

00:06:39.555 --> 00:06:42.677
half-turned, and looked back at him with an expression he

00:06:42.677 --> 00:06:45.798
could not entirely read — affection and warning braided together.

00:06:45.798 --> 00:06:48.920
"He's going to push tonight," she said. "I can feel

00:06:48.920 --> 00:06:52.041
it in the air. Don't let him pull you into

00:06:52.041 --> 00:06:55.163
a place that isn't yours." He didn't answer. She went

00:06:55.163 --> 00:06:58.284
out, and the snow blew in around her boots, and

00:06:58.284 --> 00:07:01.406
the door shut, and the kitchen was quiet again, and

00:07:01.406 --> 00:07:04.527
he stood at the counter for a long time with

00:07:04.527 --> 00:07:07.649
his hand on the warm bowl of dough and tried

00:07:07.649 --> 00:07:10.770
to figure out what part of him she had just

00:07:10.770 --> 00:07:13.892
named. The library was warmer than the kitchen. It always

00:07:13.892 --> 00:07:17.013
was. Desh wondered, each time he walked into it, whether

00:07:17.013 --> 00:07:20.135
this was an accident of architecture or a deliberate choice

00:07:20.135 --> 00:07:23.256
— whether Eleanora Voss had wanted the room of books

00:07:23.256 --> 00:07:26.378
to feel like the most welcoming room in the house

00:07:26.378 --> 00:07:29.499
— and tonight, for some reason, the question irritated him.

00:07:29.499 --> 00:07:32.621
Everything in the Keeping House was beginning to feel like

00:07:32.621 --> 00:07:35.742
it had been arranged. Every door, every chair, every angle

00:07:35.742 --> 00:07:38.864
of light. The conviction had been growing in him for

00:07:38.864 --> 00:07:41.986
a week. He was not sure it was true. He

00:07:41.986 --> 00:07:45.107
was sure it was bothering him. He set the loaf

00:07:45.107 --> 00:07:48.229
on the reading table — wrapped in a clean cotton

00:07:48.229 --> 00:07:51.350
tea towel, the crust still warm enough that he could

00:07:51.350 --> 00:07:54.472
feel it through the cloth — and beside it a

00:07:54.472 --> 00:07:57.593
small dish of olive oil he had pressed thyme into

00:07:57.593 --> 00:08:00.715
that afternoon. The brass carriage clock said five-fifty. The fire

00:08:00.715 --> 00:08:03.836
was already laid. Someone had lit it; the smaller logs

00:08:03.836 --> 00:08:06.958
had caught and the bigger ones were just beginning to.

00:08:06.958 --> 00:08:10.079
He suspected June. Margot was in the chair by the

00:08:10.079 --> 00:08:13.201
window, one leg folded under her, the new typewriter on

00:08:13.201 --> 00:08:16.322
the side table beside her — a black portable Olivetti

00:08:16.322 --> 00:08:19.444
she had found in a closet on the second floor

00:08:19.444 --> 00:08:22.565
and brought down with a kind of acquisitive triumph. The

00:08:22.565 --> 00:08:25.687
notebook was on her lap anyway, in case the typewriter

00:08:25.687 --> 00:08:28.808
proved theoretical. She looked up when he came in. "You

00:08:28.808 --> 00:08:31.930
brought bread," she said. "I brought bread." "I love you

00:08:31.930 --> 00:08:35.051
for the bread." "Don't get used to it." She smiled

00:08:35.051 --> 00:08:38.173
and went back to her notebook, and he watched her

00:08:38.173 --> 00:08:41.295
hand move across the page and felt the small, complicated

00:08:41.295 --> 00:08:44.416
affection he had come to feel for her — the

00:08:44.416 --> 00:08:47.538
affection of one over-prepared person for another, the recognition that

00:08:47.538 --> 00:08:50.659
they were two of a kind and that being two

00:08:50.659 --> 00:08:53.781
of a kind was not an unmitigated good. Lena came

00:08:53.781 --> 00:08:56.902
in. Then Noor, in her overalls, with a streak of

00:08:56.902 --> 00:09:00.024
charcoal on her wrist she had not noticed. Then Callan,

00:09:00.024 --> 00:09:03.145
who came from outside and brought the cold with him

00:09:03.145 --> 00:09:06.267
and stood in the doorway shaking snow off his cap

00:09:06.267 --> 00:09:09.388
before stepping in. He nodded at Desh — the small

00:09:09.388 --> 00:09:12.510
nod they had developed, the nod that meant I see

00:09:12.510 --> 00:09:15.631
you, I have nothing to say, and that is fine

00:09:15.631 --> 00:09:18.753
— and took his usual position against the doorframe rather

00:09:18.753 --> 00:09:21.874
than sitting. He was wearing the canvas jacket that smelled

00:09:21.874 --> 00:09:24.996
of sawdust and linseed oil, and the smell came in

00:09:24.996 --> 00:09:28.117
with him like a memory of a different room. Fen

00:09:28.117 --> 00:09:31.239
arrived last. He was carrying his laptop in one hand

00:09:31.239 --> 00:09:34.360
and a sheaf of pages in the other — the

00:09:34.360 --> 00:09:37.482
pages had a worked-over quality, with handwritten notes in the

00:09:37.482 --> 00:09:40.603
margins and ink underlines that broke the printed lines into

00:09:40.603 --> 00:09:43.725
staggered fragments. He set the laptop on the reading table

00:09:43.725 --> 00:09:46.847
beside Desh's bread. He did not look at the bread.

00:09:46.847 --> 00:09:49.968
He looked at the room. "I've written something," he said.

00:09:49.968 --> 00:09:53.090
The fire popped. The clock ticked. Desh felt the small

00:09:53.090 --> 00:09:56.211
tightening in his chest that he had felt earlier in

00:09:56.211 --> 00:09:59.333
the kitchen and had not quite understood and now understood

00:09:59.333 --> 00:10:02.454
perfectly. "Then read it," Margot said. Fen read for eight

00:10:02.454 --> 00:10:05.576
minutes. What he read was a draft of the opening

00:10:05.576 --> 00:10:08.697
of his book — the new opening, the one that

00:10:08.697 --> 00:10:11.819
had arrived after the first gathering, the one that had

00:10:11.819 --> 00:10:14.940
grown out of the sentence he had written in the

00:10:14.940 --> 00:10:18.062
dark of his cottage in early November and not deleted.

00:10:18.062 --> 00:10:21.183
He had told them this. He read with the slight

00:10:21.183 --> 00:10:24.305
tremor of a man performing a piece of himself in

00:10:24.305 --> 00:10:27.426
front of people who would judge it whether they meant

00:10:27.426 --> 00:10:30.548
to or not. It was, Desh would later admit, good.

00:10:30.548 --> 00:10:33.669
The prose had a different quality from the Fen of

00:10:33.669 --> 00:10:36.791
the first night — less performance, more nerve. There were

00:10:36.791 --> 00:10:39.912
sentences that landed: an image of his father standing in

00:10:39.912 --> 00:10:43.034
a hospital corridor in the late seventies, unable to speak

00:10:43.034 --> 00:10:46.155
the name of his own grief; a passage about the

00:10:46.155 --> 00:10:49.277
difference between paying attention and spending it, the small etymological

00:10:49.277 --> 00:10:52.399
hinge that opened a larger door. There were sentences Desh

00:10:52.399 --> 00:10:55.520
wished he had written. And there were sentences that did

00:10:55.520 --> 00:10:58.642
the thing. They came near the end. Fen had moved

00:10:58.642 --> 00:11:01.763
into a section about technology — about the architecture of

00:11:01.763 --> 00:11:04.885
distraction, the way the modern world had been engineered to

00:11:04.885 --> 00:11:08.006
fracture human focus into monetizable shards. It was a familiar

00:11:08.006 --> 00:11:11.128
argument. Desh had read versions of it for ten years.

00:11:11.128 --> 00:11:14.249
He had, in fact, helped build some of the architecture

00:11:14.249 --> 00:11:17.371
being indicted; this was not lost on him; he was

00:11:17.371 --> 00:11:20.492
prepared for it. What he was not prepared for was

00:11:20.492 --> 00:11:23.614
the turn at the end. "To attend," Fen read, "is

00:11:23.614 --> 00:11:26.735
to be free. The first freedom is the freedom to

00:11:26.735 --> 00:11:29.857
choose where the mind goes. Without that freedom, every other

00:11:29.857 --> 00:11:32.978
freedom becomes ornamental. We have built a civilization that systematically

00:11:32.978 --> 00:11:36.100
deprives us of the conditions for attention, and we have

00:11:36.100 --> 00:11:39.221
called this progress. The question this house asks — whether

00:11:39.221 --> 00:11:42.343
it knows it or not — is whether some small

00:11:42.343 --> 00:11:45.464
number of us can recover that first freedom by stepping

00:11:45.464 --> 00:11:48.586
out of the system long enough to remember what it

00:11:48.586 --> 00:11:51.707
felt like." He paused. He looked up. The firelight was

00:11:51.707 --> 00:11:54.829
on his glasses. He was, Desh saw, slightly out of

00:11:54.829 --> 00:11:57.951
breath, the way people get out of breath when they

00:11:57.951 --> 00:12:01.072
have been holding something at the edge of speech for

00:12:01.072 --> 00:12:04.194
a long time. "That's all," Fen said. "That's what I

00:12:04.194 --> 00:12:07.315
have so far." The room was quiet for a moment.

00:12:07.315 --> 00:12:10.437
Then Margot said, very softly, "That's beautiful, Fen." Lena nodded.

00:12:10.437 --> 00:12:13.558
Noor's expression had not changed. Callan, in the doorway, was

00:12:13.558 --> 00:12:16.680
looking at the floor. Desh said, "It's beautiful. And it's

00:12:16.680 --> 00:12:19.801
wrong." He had not planned to say it. The sentence

00:12:19.801 --> 00:12:22.923
walked out of his mouth ahead of him, the way

00:12:22.923 --> 00:12:26.044
sentences do when something has been waiting in the body

00:12:26.044 --> 00:12:29.166
for an exit. He felt the room rearrange itself around

00:12:29.166 --> 00:12:32.287
the words. Fen's face went still. Not surprised. Ready. The

00:12:32.287 --> 00:12:35.409
face of a man who had been waiting six weeks

00:12:35.409 --> 00:12:38.530
for this conversation. "Tell me how," Fen said. Desh set

00:12:38.530 --> 00:12:41.652
down his mug. He took his glasses off, wiped them

00:12:41.652 --> 00:12:44.773
on the hem of his shirt — the gesture his

00:12:44.773 --> 00:12:47.895
hands made when his mind was about to move faster

00:12:47.895 --> 00:12:51.016
than it should — and put them back on. "You're

00:12:51.016 --> 00:12:54.138
saying that attention is the first freedom," he said. "Fine.

00:12:54.138 --> 00:12:57.259
I can buy that. You're saying we've built a civilization

00:12:57.259 --> 00:13:00.381
that fractures attention. Also fine. I helped build some of

00:13:00.381 --> 00:13:03.503
it; I know exactly how it works. But then you

00:13:03.503 --> 00:13:06.624
say the question this house asks is whether some small

00:13:06.624 --> 00:13:09.746
number of us can recover that first freedom by stepping

00:13:09.746 --> 00:13:12.867
out of the system long enough to remember what it

00:13:12.867 --> 00:13:15.989
felt like. And I want to know who the us

00:13:15.989 --> 00:13:19.110
is." "Us is — us. The people in this room."

00:13:19.110 --> 00:13:22.232
"Right. And how did the people in this room get

00:13:22.232 --> 00:13:25.353
here?" "They were chosen." "By a trust. Endowed by a

00:13:25.353 --> 00:13:28.475
woman with enough money to build a house and feed

00:13:28.475 --> 00:13:31.596
six strangers for a year. Selected by a law firm

00:13:31.596 --> 00:13:34.718
in the state capital. With stipends just big enough to

00:13:34.718 --> 00:13:37.839
keep us from working." He could feel the heat coming

00:13:37.839 --> 00:13:40.961
up in him now. He tried to keep his voice

00:13:40.961 --> 00:13:44.082
level. "Fen, do you hear yourself? You're saying the path

00:13:44.082 --> 00:13:47.204
to the first freedom runs through a private estate on

00:13:47.204 --> 00:13:50.325
three hundred and forty acres, accessible by invitation, paid for

00:13:50.325 --> 00:13:53.447
by a dead heiress. And you're calling it recovery. As

00:13:53.447 --> 00:13:56.568
if the rest of the country is going to recover

00:13:56.568 --> 00:13:59.690
anything by reading your book." "That's not what I'm saying."

00:13:59.690 --> 00:14:02.811
"It's the structure of what you're saying. Some small number

00:14:02.811 --> 00:14:05.933
of us. That's the line. Some small number. You're describing

00:14:05.933 --> 00:14:09.055
a sanctuary and presenting it as a method." "It's not

00:14:09.055 --> 00:14:12.176
a method. It's a starting point." "For who?" "For anyone

00:14:12.176 --> 00:14:15.298
who reads the book." "Anyone who reads the book is

00:14:15.298 --> 00:14:18.419
somebody who has time to read a book about attention.

00:14:18.419 --> 00:14:21.541
Anyone who has time to read a book about attention

00:14:21.541 --> 00:14:24.662
is already most of the way to having attention. You're

00:14:24.662 --> 00:14:27.784
writing a book about water for people who already live

00:14:27.784 --> 00:14:30.905
by the river." A flicker passed across Fen's face. Annoyance.

00:14:30.905 --> 00:14:34.027
Then something else, something more interesting, something that looked like

00:14:34.027 --> 00:14:37.148
the first seam of doubt. He pushed past it. "By

00:14:37.148 --> 00:14:40.270
that logic," he said, "no one should write anything. No

00:14:40.270 --> 00:14:43.391
one should make any argument. The act of writing assumes

00:14:43.391 --> 00:14:46.513
a reader who is already in the conversation. That's true

00:14:46.513 --> 00:14:49.634
of every book ever published. It's a ridiculous standard." "I'm

00:14:49.634 --> 00:14:52.756
not saying don't write the book. I'm saying don't pretend

00:14:52.756 --> 00:14:55.877
the book is for everyone when it's for the people

00:14:55.877 --> 00:14:58.999
who can afford to retreat. Be honest about who the

00:14:58.999 --> 00:15:02.120
audience is and what the audience already has." "Honest." Fen's

00:15:02.120 --> 00:15:05.242
voice had picked up an edge. "You're going to lecture

00:15:05.242 --> 00:15:08.363
me about honesty." "Yes." "You came here from a startup

00:15:08.363 --> 00:15:11.485
whose entire business model was selling attention back to the

00:15:11.485 --> 00:15:14.607
people you took it from. You built the architecture of

00:15:14.607 --> 00:15:17.728
distraction. You profited from it until it broke you, and

00:15:17.728 --> 00:15:20.850
then you came to a stone house in the woods

00:15:20.850 --> 00:15:23.971
to write about communal cooking, and now you're going to

00:15:23.971 --> 00:15:27.093
tell me that I should be honest about my position?"

00:15:27.093 --> 00:15:30.214
The room had gone very still. Desh felt the words

00:15:30.214 --> 00:15:33.336
land — felt them physically, in the place above his

00:15:33.336 --> 00:15:36.457
solar plexus where he had felt every difficult conversation he

00:15:36.457 --> 00:15:39.579
had ever had with his father — and he understood,

00:15:39.579 --> 00:15:42.700
with a clarity that arrived too late to be useful,

00:15:42.700 --> 00:15:45.822
that Fen had been preparing this answer for as long

00:15:45.822 --> 00:15:48.943
as Desh had been preparing his question. They had been

00:15:48.943 --> 00:15:52.065
writing each other's chapters in their separate cottages for six

00:15:52.065 --> 00:15:55.186
weeks. "You're right," Desh said. His voice had gone quiet.

00:15:55.186 --> 00:15:58.308
"I did all of that. And I'm not going to

00:15:58.308 --> 00:16:01.429
defend it. But I never sold it as freedom." "Neither

00:16:01.429 --> 00:16:04.551
am I." "You just did. You read it out loud."

00:16:04.551 --> 00:16:07.672
"I said attention was the first freedom. I did not

00:16:07.672 --> 00:16:10.794
say my book was a freedom." "You said the question

00:16:10.794 --> 00:16:13.915
this house asks is whether some small number of us

00:16:13.915 --> 00:16:17.037
can recover that freedom. Right here. Right now. In a

00:16:17.037 --> 00:16:20.159
room with one person who's actually worked with his hands

00:16:20.159 --> 00:16:23.280
for a living and one person who left a marriage

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:26.402
and one person whose mother spent twenty-five years moving from

00:16:26.402 --> 00:16:29.523
base to base, and you said us, and you meant

00:16:29.523 --> 00:16:32.645
us, and I'm telling you the us is the problem."

00:16:32.645 --> 00:16:35.766
He stopped. He could hear his own breathing. He was

00:16:35.766 --> 00:16:38.888
not yelling. Neither was Fen. The argument had the contained,

00:16:38.888 --> 00:16:42.009
deliberate cadence of two people who had spent their lives

00:16:42.009 --> 00:16:45.131
learning to win by sounding calm, and the contained quality

00:16:45.131 --> 00:16:48.252
of it was, somehow, worse than yelling would have been.

00:16:48.252 --> 00:16:51.374
Yelling would have let some pressure out. Margot put down

00:16:51.374 --> 00:16:54.495
her notebook. "Okay," she said. "Okay. Let me — can

00:16:54.495 --> 00:16:57.617
I — can I try something?" She had her policy-meeting

00:16:57.617 --> 00:17:00.738
voice on. He recognized it. He had heard it on

00:17:00.738 --> 00:17:03.860
a Tuesday in October when she had explained, over coffee,

00:17:03.860 --> 00:17:06.981
the framework she used for facilitating stakeholder sessions in her

00:17:06.981 --> 00:17:10.103
former life, when she had been the woman in the

00:17:10.103 --> 00:17:13.224
room with the agenda, and he loved her for it

00:17:13.224 --> 00:17:16.346
and he also did not want it now. "Margot," he

00:17:16.346 --> 00:17:19.467
said. "Just — I want to name what I'm hearing.

00:17:19.467 --> 00:17:22.589
Desh, I think you're saying that the framing of the

00:17:22.589 --> 00:17:25.711
book elides the material conditions that make attention possible, and

00:17:25.711 --> 00:17:28.832
that's a real critique. Fen, I think you're saying that

00:17:28.832 --> 00:17:31.954
the book is a starting point rather than a complete

00:17:31.954 --> 00:17:35.075
program, and that's a fair clarification. I wonder if we

00:17:35.075 --> 00:17:38.197
could—" "Margot." It was Fen this time. "Please don't." "I'm

00:17:38.197 --> 00:17:41.318
trying to—" "I know what you're trying to do. And

00:17:41.318 --> 00:17:44.440
I'm asking you not to." She looked stricken for a

00:17:44.440 --> 00:17:47.561
half-second, the way a person looks when they reach for

00:17:47.561 --> 00:17:50.683
the role they have always been good at and find

00:17:50.683 --> 00:17:53.804
it isn't there. Then she sat back. Her hand went

00:17:53.804 --> 00:17:56.926
to her notebook. It did not pick the notebook up.

00:17:56.926 --> 00:18:00.047
It rested on the cover, the way a hand rests

00:18:00.047 --> 00:18:03.169
on a closed door it is not going to open.

00:18:03.169 --> 00:18:06.290
Desh felt the small, sharp guilt of having been complicit

00:18:06.290 --> 00:18:09.412
in her exposure. He had not asked her to mediate.

00:18:09.412 --> 00:18:12.533
He also had not stopped her. He had let her

00:18:12.533 --> 00:18:15.655
step in front of the argument because he had wanted,

00:18:15.655 --> 00:18:18.776
for one second, to be a person who was being

00:18:18.776 --> 00:18:21.898
defended. He looked at her. He said, very quietly, "I'm

00:18:21.898 --> 00:18:25.019
sorry." She did not look up. "It's fine." It was

00:18:25.019 --> 00:18:28.141
not fine. He let it not be fine. Across the

00:18:28.141 --> 00:18:31.263
room, against the doorframe, Callan moved. It was a small

00:18:31.263 --> 00:18:34.384
motion at first — a shift of weight, the way

00:18:34.384 --> 00:18:37.506
a person who has been standing very still for a

00:18:37.506 --> 00:18:40.627
long time prepares to be standing differently. Desh saw it

00:18:40.627 --> 00:18:43.749
in his peripheral vision. He turned his head. Callan was

00:18:43.749 --> 00:18:46.870
looking at the rug. His arms were uncrossed. His jaw

00:18:46.870 --> 00:18:49.992
was set in the way men set their jaws when

00:18:49.992 --> 00:18:53.113
they are deciding something. The firelight was on the line

00:18:53.113 --> 00:18:56.235
of his cheek. The scar on his left forearm —

00:18:56.235 --> 00:18:59.356
the table-saw scar, a thin pale ribbon Desh had cataloged

00:18:59.356 --> 00:19:02.478
the first week without meaning to — was visible in

00:19:02.478 --> 00:19:05.599
the rolled cuff of his sleeve. He looked up. He

00:19:05.599 --> 00:19:08.721
looked at Fen, briefly, without expression. Then he looked at

00:19:08.721 --> 00:19:11.842
Desh. "I'm going to step outside," he said. It was

00:19:11.842 --> 00:19:14.964
not a protest. It was not a rebuke. It was

00:19:14.964 --> 00:19:18.085
a man telling the room what he needed to do

00:19:18.085 --> 00:19:21.207
for himself. The voice was level. The voice had, if

00:19:21.207 --> 00:19:24.328
anything, the tenderness of a man trying not to make

00:19:24.328 --> 00:19:27.450
his exit a verdict. He pushed off the doorframe. He

00:19:27.450 --> 00:19:30.571
picked up his cap from the side table where he

00:19:30.571 --> 00:19:33.693
had set it. He pulled it on. He turned the

00:19:33.693 --> 00:19:36.815
brass handle of the library door, and the cold from

00:19:36.815 --> 00:19:39.936
the hallway came into the warm room — not the

00:19:39.936 --> 00:19:43.058
inside cold, the outside cold, the snow-cold that had been

00:19:43.058 --> 00:19:46.179
pressing against the windows all evening — and he stepped

00:19:46.179 --> 00:19:49.301
through the threshold and pulled the door closed behind him

00:19:49.301 --> 00:19:52.422
with a soft, deliberate click that was, in its quietness,

00:19:52.422 --> 00:19:55.544
the loudest thing that had happened in the room. For

00:19:55.544 --> 00:19:58.665
a moment, no one moved. Then Noor said, "Well." The

00:19:58.665 --> 00:20:01.787
argument did not resume. Whatever pressure had been driving it

00:20:01.787 --> 00:20:04.908
had gone out of the room with Callan, the way

00:20:04.908 --> 00:20:08.030
air goes out of a room when a window opens.

00:20:08.030 --> 00:20:11.151
Fen stood up. He picked up his pages and tapped

00:20:11.151 --> 00:20:14.273
them once on the table to align them and held

00:20:14.273 --> 00:20:17.394
them against his chest like a man holding a wound

00:20:17.394 --> 00:20:20.516
he had not realized he was bleeding from. "I think

00:20:20.516 --> 00:20:23.637
I'm going to —" he began. He did not finish

00:20:23.637 --> 00:20:26.759
the sentence. He walked to the door and opened it

00:20:26.759 --> 00:20:29.880
and went out. Lena looked at Desh. She did not

00:20:29.880 --> 00:20:33.002
say anything. There was something in her expression that he

00:20:33.002 --> 00:20:36.123
could not name and did not want named. Noor uncoiled

00:20:36.123 --> 00:20:39.245
herself from the floor. She picked up the loaf of

00:20:39.245 --> 00:20:42.367
bread from the table — the loaf Desh had wrapped

00:20:42.367 --> 00:20:45.488
in the towel and placed beside the dish of thyme

00:20:45.488 --> 00:20:48.610
oil — and she carried it over to him and

00:20:48.610 --> 00:20:51.731
put it in his hands. "Take it back to the

00:20:51.731 --> 00:20:54.853
kitchen," she said. "Nobody's going to eat it tonight." He

00:20:54.853 --> 00:20:57.974
took it. The crust was no longer warm. He went

00:20:57.974 --> 00:21:01.096
back to the kitchen with the bread. The light was

00:21:01.096 --> 00:21:04.217
on. He had left it on. The covered bowl with

00:21:04.217 --> 00:21:07.339
the second loaf was on the counter where he had

00:21:07.339 --> 00:21:10.460
abandoned it; the rise had peaked and was on its

00:21:10.460 --> 00:21:13.582
way to overproof, the dough sagging slightly in the center

00:21:13.582 --> 00:21:16.703
the way dough sags when it has been waiting too

00:21:16.703 --> 00:21:19.825
long for hands. He set the first loaf on the

00:21:19.825 --> 00:21:22.946
cooling rack. He uncovered the bowl. He looked at the

00:21:22.946 --> 00:21:26.068
dough. He should punch it down and shape it and

00:21:26.068 --> 00:21:29.189
put it in the pan and let it have its

00:21:29.189 --> 00:21:32.311
second rise. He should preserve the bread because the bread

00:21:32.311 --> 00:21:35.432
had done nothing wrong. He punched it down. He shaped

00:21:35.432 --> 00:21:38.554
it. He greased the pan. He laid the loaf in.

00:21:38.554 --> 00:21:41.675
He covered it with a clean towel. His hands were

00:21:41.675 --> 00:21:44.797
doing the work that hands do when the rest of

00:21:44.797 --> 00:21:47.919
you has gone elsewhere. He could feel his pulse in

00:21:47.919 --> 00:21:51.040
his lower lip, in the place Lena had said was

00:21:51.040 --> 00:21:54.162
bruised. He pressed the spot with his tongue. She was

00:21:54.162 --> 00:21:57.283
right; there was a small swelling there. He had not

00:21:57.283 --> 00:22:00.405
noticed it. He had not noticed any of the things

00:22:00.405 --> 00:22:03.526
she had named. The grinding teeth. The four a.m. waking.

00:22:03.526 --> 00:22:06.648
The way the small bruises of his unhappiness were collecting

00:22:06.648 --> 00:22:09.769
on his body without his permission. He stood at the

00:22:09.769 --> 00:22:12.891
counter and looked out at the snow. It was still

00:22:12.891 --> 00:22:16.012
falling. The path lights along the gravel had been buried

00:22:16.012 --> 00:22:19.134
at their bases, the bulbs glowing through caps of white.

00:22:19.134 --> 00:22:22.255
Somewhere out there Callan was walking — or had stopped

00:22:22.255 --> 00:22:25.377
walking — and somewhere else Fen was sitting with his

00:22:25.377 --> 00:22:28.498
pages and his shame, and somewhere else Margot was, very

00:22:28.498 --> 00:22:31.620
quietly, putting her notebook on a high shelf because the

00:22:31.620 --> 00:22:34.741
role she had reached for had not been there. He

00:22:34.741 --> 00:22:37.863
thought: I was right. He thought: And it cost me

00:22:37.863 --> 00:22:40.984
something I cannot yet name. He thought, with the helpless

00:22:40.984 --> 00:22:44.106
precision of a man who could not stop thinking in

00:22:44.106 --> 00:22:47.227
patterns even when the patterns were the problem: He used

00:22:47.227 --> 00:22:50.349
my biography against me, which means I have been holding

00:22:50.349 --> 00:22:53.471
his against him for six weeks, and we have both

00:22:53.471 --> 00:22:56.592
been doing this in private the way two people sharpen

00:22:56.592 --> 00:22:59.714
knives in separate rooms. And the thing we were sharpening

00:22:59.714 --> 00:23:02.835
for was tonight. And we both knew it. And neither

00:23:02.835 --> 00:23:05.957
of us said so. He picked up the notebook from

00:23:05.957 --> 00:23:09.078
the counter. The page was open to the line he

00:23:09.078 --> 00:23:12.200
had written that afternoon — I am bringing bread because

00:23:12.200 --> 00:23:15.321
I do not know what else I have to say

00:23:15.321 --> 00:23:18.443
— with the thin line drawn through it and not

00:23:18.443 --> 00:23:21.564
erased. He picked up the pen. He wrote, beneath the

00:23:21.564 --> 00:23:24.686
line: I had something to say. I said it. I

00:23:24.686 --> 00:23:27.807
was right and I was cruel and I do not

00:23:27.807 --> 00:23:30.929
know if those two things can occupy the same sentence

00:23:30.929 --> 00:23:34.050
honestly. The bread is in its second rise. The snow

00:23:34.050 --> 00:23:37.172
has not stopped. Callan walked out and I am sitting

00:23:37.172 --> 00:23:40.293
in a kitchen at eight in the evening writing about

00:23:40.293 --> 00:23:43.415
it, which is, I notice, a thing I could not

00:23:43.415 --> 00:23:46.536
have stopped myself from doing if I tried. He put

00:23:46.536 --> 00:23:49.658
the pen down. He thought about his mother, in the

00:23:49.658 --> 00:23:52.779
house in New Jersey, who would not have understood any

00:23:52.779 --> 00:23:55.901
of this. Who had asked him, on the phone two

00:23:55.901 --> 00:23:59.023
weeks ago, when he was going to come back to

00:23:59.023 --> 00:24:02.144
real work. He had not had an answer for her

00:24:02.144 --> 00:24:05.266
then. He did not have one now. He had only

00:24:05.266 --> 00:24:08.387
the small, terrible insight that the argument tonight had been,

00:24:08.387 --> 00:24:11.509
in part, his way of proving that he could still

00:24:11.509 --> 00:24:14.630
do the kind of thinking his parents would have respected

00:24:14.630 --> 00:24:17.752
— sharp, structural, victorious — even though he had come

00:24:17.752 --> 00:24:20.873
here, supposedly, to learn a different kind of being. He

00:24:20.873 --> 00:24:23.995
thought about Callan walking out. Not the gesture but the

00:24:23.995 --> 00:24:27.116
quality of it. The slowness. The deliberateness. The refusal to

00:24:27.116 --> 00:24:30.238
make the leaving into a statement. Callan had not been

00:24:30.238 --> 00:24:33.359
performing anything. He had simply removed his body from a

00:24:33.359 --> 00:24:36.481
room in which his body had not been the subject

00:24:36.481 --> 00:24:39.602
of anyone's argument and yet had somehow been the ground

00:24:39.602 --> 00:24:42.724
on which the argument was being fought. Desh was not,

00:24:42.724 --> 00:24:45.845
he understood, going to apologize to Fen tonight. It was

00:24:45.845 --> 00:24:48.967
not yet the right shape of conversation. He might never

00:24:48.967 --> 00:24:52.088
apologize, exactly; an apology would falsify what he had said,

00:24:52.088 --> 00:24:55.210
which had been true, even if the saying of it

00:24:55.210 --> 00:24:58.331
had also been a kind of violence. What he was

00:24:58.331 --> 00:25:01.453
going to do — what he could feel forming in

00:25:01.453 --> 00:25:04.575
his chest, the way bread forms when you give it

00:25:04.575 --> 00:25:07.696
the right conditions and walk away — was something else.

00:25:07.696 --> 00:25:10.818
Something slower. Something that would require him to stop being

00:25:10.818 --> 00:25:13.939
right for long enough to be honest. He covered the

00:25:13.939 --> 00:25:17.061
loaf. He turned the kitchen light off. He stood in

00:25:17.061 --> 00:25:20.182
the dark for a moment, and the snow outside had

00:25:20.182 --> 00:25:23.304
a faint blue self-light, the way snow does at night,

00:25:23.304 --> 00:25:26.425
the way the world becomes legible in winter even when

00:25:26.425 --> 00:25:29.547
the lamps are out. Then, because he could not help

00:25:29.547 --> 00:25:32.668
himself, because his hands had been making things since he

00:25:32.668 --> 00:25:35.790
was eleven and would keep making things until they could

00:25:35.790 --> 00:25:38.911
not, he reached up and took down the small enameled

00:25:38.911 --> 00:25:42.033
tin he kept above the stove and opened it and

00:25:42.033 --> 00:25:45.154
shook out a half-dozen dates and arranged them on a

00:25:45.154 --> 00:25:48.276
small white plate and went to the back door and

00:25:48.276 --> 00:25:51.397
pulled on his boots and his coat and walked out

00:25:51.397 --> 00:25:54.519
into the falling snow toward the barn, where a single

00:25:54.519 --> 00:25:57.640
yellow light was on in the high window, and where

00:25:57.640 --> 00:26:00.762
a man he had embarrassed in front of a room

00:26:00.762 --> 00:26:03.884
— without ever once meaning to — was, presumably, working

00:26:03.884 --> 00:26:07.005
with his hands because hands were the only language certain

00:26:07.005 --> 00:26:10.127
people had been given and he had, tonight, made the

00:26:10.127 --> 00:26:13.248
room forget that. He would not go inside. He would

00:26:13.248 --> 00:26:16.370
set the plate on the threshold. He would walk back

00:26:16.370 --> 00:26:19.491
to the house through the snow, which was deep enough

00:26:19.491 --> 00:26:22.613
now to reach the laces of his boots, and he

00:26:22.613 --> 00:26:25.734
would not look up at the high window to see

00:26:25.734 --> 00:26:28.856
if Callan saw him, because the looking-up would have been

00:26:28.856 --> 00:26:31.977
the false note, the gesture that asked for credit. He

00:26:31.977 --> 00:26:35.099
set the plate down on the wide oak board that

00:26:35.099 --> 00:26:38.220
ran across the bottom of the barn door. The dates

00:26:38.220 --> 00:26:41.342
looked very dark against the white plate against the white

00:26:41.342 --> 00:26:44.463
snow. He turned and walked back the way he had

00:26:44.463 --> 00:26:47.585
come. The snow was still falling. The wind had picked

00:26:47.585 --> 00:26:50.706
up. The high window of the barn glowed yellow above

00:26:50.706 --> 00:26:53.828
him, and he did not look at it, and he

00:26:53.828 --> 00:26:56.949
did not know if anyone was watching him from inside,

00:26:56.949 --> 00:27:00.071
and he kept walking, and his footprints behind him were

00:27:00.071 --> 00:27:02.256
already, a little, beginning to fill in.
